# Build the Observer as an Activated Pi Extension

## Question

Convert the observer charter (`dark-wizard/.brain/tasks/observer-loop-charter.svx`)
from a kickoff prompt into an activated pi extension that injects the
observer constitution into the SYSTEM PROMPT (Amendment 3 of the topology
ticket). Study existing extensions (`~/.pi/agent/extensions/` —
memory-capture, herdr-name-sync, herdr-callsign) for the API. Requirements:

- Activation is explicit (flag/env/config), never default — only the
  observer session gets observer identity.
- Charter content sourced from the svx file at session start (file remains
  the editable truth; extension is the injection mechanism).
- Cache-aware: charter injects as a stable prefix; anything dynamic
  (cursor value, date) arrives in tick prompts, not the system prompt.
- Restart story: `observer-tick.sh` gains an ensure-session step — if the
  pane's pi is dead, relaunch `pi` with the extension activated; identity
  comes from the extension, state from the cursor. Include daily session
  rotation (fresh session each morning, cursor carries over).
- Receipts: a tick executed under extension identity with no kickoff
  prompt; a simulated compaction (or long session) showing the charter
  still governs.

## Addendum (Joel, 2026-07-12): headless tool policy

The extension MUST disable interactive/blocking tools for observer sessions —
MCQ/ask-user style prompts, quick-pick dialogs, anything that waits on a
human. A headless daemon that asks a question deadlocks until the next human
visit (the quick-pick modal that swallowed a tick during today's migration is
the receipt). Enumerate pi's interactive tool surface from source/extensions
and turn all of it off under observer identity; when the observer would have
asked, it instead records the question in its tick report and proceeds
conservatively (doubt → sensitive, gaps → report loudly).
